You said:
i am creating an agentic ai based job search and resume tailoring software in python with GUI created in Tkinter. Provide me a detailed architecture of this software, with all the modules used. It will do the following tasks: - input the user resume and job search keywords, location. - search popular job sites and load job descriptions. - score job descriptions based on similarity with the given resume. do not show the job descriptions having scores below the threshold. - When user selects one such job description, do some more research about the company. - based on job description and company information, tailor the resume to fit the job needs. - calculate the score this tailored resume will get while passed through the ATS system. -
2/2
ChatGPT said:

Nice thats a great project. Below Ive laid out a detailed architecture for an agentic job-search + resume-tailoring desktop app in Python with a Tkinter GUI. It covers modules, responsibilities, data flows, algorithms, integration points, storage, security, and a suggested dev roadmap and file structure so you can start implementing right away.

1 High-level overview

User inputs resume + job search query job fetcher collects job postings job parser + embedding engine score each posting vs. resume GUI shows only postings above threshold user picks a posting company researcher gathers company data tailoring engine (LLM + rules) rewrites/rescores resume ATS simulator estimates ATS pass score UI shows tailored resume, score, and export options.

2 Top-level modules (with responsibilities)

  1. GUI (tk_gui)

    • Build Tkinter windows, dialogs, and flows.

    • Input forms for resume upload (PDF/DOCX/TXT), keywords, location, threshold.

    • Job list viewer with score, expand/collapse job details (if allowed), selection controls.

    • Tailoring result viewer (diff/highlighted changes), ATS score display, export buttons (PDF, DOCX).

    • Status/log pane showing background tasks progress.

  2. Orchestrator / Controller (controller)

    • Coordinates between GUI and backend modules.

    • Accepts user actions and triggers jobs, returns results to GUI.

    • Manages state, retries, error handling.

  3. Input & Parsing (input_parser)

    • Resume loader: accepts PDF/DOCX/TXT; extracts text and structured blocks (contact, experience, education).

    • Job descriptor loader: normalizes job description text from scrapers/APIs.

    • Use libraries: pdfminer.six or PyMuPDF for PDFs, python-docx for DOCX.

  4. Job Search & Scraper (job_fetcher)

    • Connectors for job sites (Indeed, LinkedIn, Glassdoor, Monster, company career pages, etc.).

    • Support: official APIs when available, HTML scraping (requests + BeautifulSoup), or Selenium/Playwright for heavy JS pages.

    • Respect robots.txt and rate limits; provide proxy integration, backoff logic, caching.

    • Return: raw job page, parsed job title, location, posted date, job description, job URL, company name.

  5. Job Parser & Normalizer (job_parser)

    • Extract sections: responsibilities, qualifications (must/desired), skills, seniority, location, employment type.

    • Clean text (remove boilerplate, formatting).

    • Use simple heuristics + rules and optional NER with spaCy.

  6. Resume Parser (resume_parser)

    • Extract sections from resume: summary, experience bullets, skills, education, certifications.

    • Produce both raw text and structured JSON representation for matching.

    • Use spaCy + rule-based parsing (dates, company names, role titles) plus layout heuristics.

  7. Embedding Engine (embeddings)

    • Convert resume and job description (and sub-sections) into vector embeddings.

    • Options: sentence-transformers (e.g., all-MiniLM-L6-v2) for local embedding, or remote LLM embeddings.

    • Provide semantic search similarity and fine-grained matching (section-to-section).

  8. Similarity Scorer & Filter (scorer)

    • Compute similarity scores at multiple granularities:

      • Whole-document similarity (resume job description).

      • Section similarity (skills list required skills).

      • Weighted composite score (weights configurable).

    • Filter out jobs below threshold.

    • Produce feature contributions for explainability (e.g., skill match %).

  9. Company Researcher (company_research)

    • When user selects a job, fetch company details:

      • company description, size, industry, locations

      • main tech stack / mentions (from job postings or LinkedIn)

      • Glassdoor ratings, latest news (optional), Crunchbase funding, LinkedIn company page snapshot

    • Use APIs where possible (LinkedIn is restricted; rely on OpenGraph metadata, company website, news APIs).

    • Summarize key signals helpful for tailoring (tone, values, buzzwords).

  10. Tailoring Engine (tailor)

    • Uses an LLM (locally or API) combined with rule-based edits.

    • Steps:

      1. Extract target keywords and required skills from job.

      2. Re-rank resume bullets by relevance; suggest rewording bullets to include target keywords and quantify achievements.

      3. Generate tailored resume versions at different levels: minimal, moderate, aggressive.

    • Keep an audit trail (diffs) showing what changed and why.

  11. ATS Simulator (ats_sim)

    • Simulate typical ATS parsing & scoring:

      • Parse applicant text as ATS would (flatten resume to plain text, extract header info).

      • Keyword presence/absence, keyword frequency (but avoid keyword stuffing penalties).

      • Match job title and skills with fuzzy matching.

      • Score using configurable weighting: required skills, preferred skills, education, certifications, years of experience.

      • Output: predicted ATS pass probability / score and areas to improve.

  12. Storage & Cache (storage)

    • Local DB for caching jobs, embeddings, user sessions.

    • Options: SQLite for local, small Redis if needed.

    • Encrypted storage for resumes and PII (on-disk encryption).

  13. Workers & Concurrency (workers)

    • Thread/process pool to run web scraping, embeddings, LLM calls off the Tkinter main thread.

    • Use concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecutor or multiprocessing for CPU-bound tasks.

  14. Logging, Telemetry & Error Handling (logging_util)

    • Structured logs, error capture, user-friendly error messages.

    • Optionally anonymized telemetry for usage improvements.

  15. Security & Privacy (security)

    • Local-only mode vs cloud mode; explicit consent for webhook/remote LLM/Aggregation.

    • PII redaction, optional encryption, secure storage for API keys.

  16. Testing & CI (testing)

    • Unit tests, integration tests (mocking external APIs), end-to-end tests for GUI flows (e.g., using pytest + pytest-qt or pywinauto).

4 Scoring design (explainable, numeric)

Compute a composite job_match_score (0100). Example weighting:

  • Skills match (40%): semantic overlap between job required skills and resume skills (embedding cosine or exact match).

  • Experience relevance (25%): overlap of experience bullets embeddings with responsibility section.

  • Title & seniority match (10%): exact/fuzzy match of role titles + years of experience check.

  • Education/certs (10%): presence of required credentials.

  • Soft-skills / culture keywords (5%): company tone/values match.

  • Location/remote (10%): location match or remote preference.

Detailed example calculation (digit-by-digit safe approach for clarity):

  • Suppose skill_match = 0.78 (cosine similarity)

  • experience_match = 0.65

  • title_match = 0.9

  • education_match = 1.0

  • culture_match = 0.4

  • location_match = 1.0

Composite = round( (0.7840 + 0.6525 + 0.910 + 1.010 + 0.45 + 1.010) )
Step-by-step:

  • 0.78 * 40 = 31.2

  • 0.65 * 25 = 16.25

  • 0.9 * 10 = 9.0

  • 1.0 * 10 = 10.0

  • 0.4 * 5 = 2.0

  • 1.0 * 10 = 10.0

  • Sum = 31.2 + 16.25 + 9.0 + 10.0 + 2.0 + 10.0 = 78.45

  • Round 78 (out of 100)

Set a threshold, e.g., 60. Jobs < threshold are not shown.

5 ATS Simulator implementation notes

ATS systems behave differently but common patterns:

  • Many parse text sequentially; PDFs with fancy layouts can fail. Simulate by:

    1. Converting resume to plain text (preserve newlines).

    2. Extract title, experience, skills via regex/NER.

    3. Keyword match: required skills exact + fuzzy (Levenshtein with python-Levenshtein).

    4. Calculate keyword coverage ratio:

      • required_found / required_total.

      • preferred_found / preferred_total.

    5. Penalize for missing contact fields or unreadable sections.

    6. Compute an ATS score (0100) from weighted coverage + parsing confidence.

Suggested scoring rule (ATS):

  • Required keywords coverage (50%)

  • Preferred keywords coverage (20%)

  • Parsing confidence/format (15%)

  • Title/experience confirmation (15%)

Also provide suggestions to make the resume ATS-friendlier:

  • Flattened headings (e.g., "Experience" exactly).

  • Use standard job titles and acronyms (e.g., "SQL" vs "Structured Query Language").

  • Avoid headers/footers for contact info.

6 Tailoring Engine approach & safety

  • Use an LLM (OpenAI/other) or a local LLM via LangChain + local model.

  • Prompt design (examples):

    • Input: job description, company summary, parsed resume JSON.

    • Output: revised resume bullets + a short explanation for each change.

  • Combine with rule-based editing:

    • Maintain achievements (do not hallucinate numbers).

    • If an LLM suggests quantified metrics that arent in the original resume, flag them as suggestions rather than auto-insert.

  • Provide multiple tailoring levels (safe vs aggressive) and let user approve each change.

  • Keep an audit log of original + new text.

7 Company research sources & methods

  • Prioritize official sources: company website (About, Careers), LinkedIn company page (metadata), Crunchbase (if applicable).

  • Supplement with news: use news APIs (NewsAPI.org) to surface recent relevant events.

  • Glassdoor for culture/ratings (note scraping limitations / rate limits).

  • For tech stacks: search repo mentions, job postings, StackShare.

  • Return a short company profile and a list of top keywords/missions/values.

8 GUI layout & user flows (Tkinter)

  • Main window: left pane = search inputs + filters. Center pane = job results list (sortable by score). Right pane = selected job detail + company summary + action buttons (Tailor Resume, Research).

  • Modal: Resume Upload (preview), Tailoring options (level slider, preference toggles).

  • Modal: Tailor result with side-by-side diff (original vs tailored) and accept/reject per-section.

  • Background tasks must never run on the Tk main thread use worker threads and update GUI via after().

9 Concurrency, rate limiting & robustness

  • Scraping and LLM calls are I/O-bound handle with ThreadPoolExecutor.

  • Use bounded queues to avoid thread explosion.

  • Implement per-site rate-limiting; implement retries with exponential backoff.

  • Use caching for job pages and embeddings to avoid repeated calls.

10 Privacy, security & legal

  • Be explicit about PII handling. Offer:

    • Local-only mode (no network calls).

    • Encrypted cloud sync (user opt-in).

  • Securely store API keys (OS keyring).

  • Respect robots.txt and terms of serviceprefer official APIs.

  • Provide a clear EULA/privacy policy for users.

  • GUI: tkinter

  • HTTP & scraping: requests, aiohttp (async variant), BeautifulSoup (bs4), Selenium or playwright for JS-heavy sites

  • Logging: structlog or built-in logging

14 Example tailoring pipeline (detailed steps)

  1. Extract required/desired keywords from job description (job_parser).

  2. Identify top 6 resume bullets that best match responsibilities (embedding similarity).

  3. For each bullet:

    • If it contains matching activity but needs keyword alignment, suggest rewording with synonyms/keywords found in job (LLM prompt).

    • If it lacks metrics, propose a rephrasing that uses existing numbers or suggests placeholders (marked as suggestions).

  4. Re-order skills section to list required skills first (exact strings preferred).

  5. Generate final tailored resume (text + structured sections).

  6. Run ATS simulator and output the predicted score plus targeted actions.

15 Testing, metrics and evaluation

  • Unit tests for parsing, scoring, and embedding pipelines.

  • Integration tests with mocked job sites.

  • Evaluate scoring pipeline on a small dataset: collect a set of job-posting/resume pairs and measure whether the scoring ranks the "relevant" jobs higher.

  • For ATS simulator accuracy, test against anonymized real applicant submissions if possible.

16 Roadmap / phased implementation

Phase 1 (MVP):

  • Resume upload/parsing.

  • Single-site job fetcher (e.g., Indeed).

  • Embeddings + similarity scoring.

  • Tkinter UI with job list and selection.

  • Tailor basic rewrite with templated rules (no LLM).

  • Basic ATS heuristics.

Phase 2:

  • Add more connectors and robust scraping.

  • LLM-based tailoring (API or local).

  • Company researcher module.

  • ATS simulator improvements and export (PDF/DOCX).

Phase 3:

  • Vector DB (FAISS) + fast semantic search across cached jobs.

  • User accounts/cloud sync (optional).

  • A/B testing and telemetry to tune weighting.

17 UX & product suggestions

  • Let users set the score threshold with examples of what each threshold roughly means (60 = ok fit, 80 = strong fit).

  • Provide explain buttons that break down the scoring per job (skill overlap, exp match).

  • Save multiple tailored resume versions and show a diff before exporting.

  • Provide "why was this job filtered out?" feedback for transparency.

18 Potential challenges & mitigations

  • Scraping limitations / ToS: prefer official APIs; cache aggressively; implement polite scrapers and rate limits.

  • Hallucinations by LLM: never automatically insert specific numbers; flag any LLM-generated claims for user approval.

  • Resume parsing edge-cases: allow user to correct parsed sections manually in the UI.

  • Privacy: provide local-only option and clear data deletion controls.

Excellent question youre thinking about agentic structure, which is exactly right for a system like this.
Lets expand the previous architecture to show where the AI/agent logic lives, how the tools are exposed to the agents, and how they coordinate across modules.

1. Agentic AI Layer Overview

Youll have a dedicated agents/ package that contains:

  • The core agent framework (controller, memory, tool management).

  • Specialized task agents (job search agent, scoring agent, tailoring agent, company research agent, ATS agent).

  • A shared tool registry where all AI tools are defined and callable.

This separation keeps your AI logic cleanly modular the rest of the app (GUI, storage, etc.) just sends high-level commands to the Agent Orchestrator, and the agents decide how to act.

4. Agentic Architecture Details

agents/base_agent.py

Abstract base class all agents inherit from.

python
class BaseAgent:
    def __init__(self, name, memory=None, tools=None):
        self.name = name
        self.memory = memory or {}
        self.tools = tools or {}

    def observe(self, event):
        """Store observation in short-term memory"""
        self.memory.setdefault("observations", []).append(event)

    def think(self, goal):
        """Decide what action/tool to use"""
        raise NotImplementedError

    def act(self, action, **kwargs):
        """Invoke a tool or perform internal reasoning"""
        if action in self.tools:
            return self.tools[action](**kwargs)
        else:
            raise ValueError(f"Unknown action/tool: {action}")

agents/tools/tool_registry.py

Registers all callable tools for all agents.

python
from . import scraping_tools, embedding_tools, parsing_tools, tailoring_tools, ats_tools, research_tools

def get_tool_registry():
    return {
        "search_jobs": scraping_tools.search_jobs,
        "parse_resume": parsing_tools.parse_resume,
        "embed_text": embedding_tools.embed_text,
        "score_similarity": embedding_tools.score_similarity,
        "tailor_resume": tailoring_tools.tailor_resume,
        "simulate_ats": ats_tools.simulate_ats,
        "research_company": research_tools.research_company,
    }

Each agent only loads the subset of tools relevant to its domain.

agents/agent_orchestrator.py

The central coordinator that chains agents together:

  • Manages the flow (Resume Job Search Scoring Tailoring ATS).

  • Handles context passing between agents.

  • Could be rule-based or LLM-driven (for true autonomous reasoning).

Example (simplified):

python
from .job_search_agent import JobSearchAgent
from .scoring_agent import ScoringAgent
from .tailoring_agent import TailoringAgent
from .ats_agent import ATSAgent
from .research_agent import ResearchAgent

class AgentOrchestrator:
    def __init__(self, resume, user_prefs):
        self.resume = resume
        self.user_prefs = user_prefs
        self.agents = {
            "search": JobSearchAgent(),
            "score": ScoringAgent(),
            "research": ResearchAgent(),
            "tailor": TailoringAgent(),
            "ats": ATSAgent(),
        }

    def run_pipeline(self, keywords, location, threshold=60):
        jobs = self.agents["search"].think_and_act(keywords=keywords, location=location)
        scored = self.agents["score"].think_and_act(resume=self.resume, jobs=jobs)
        filtered = [j for j in scored if j["score"] >= threshold]
        return filtered

    def tailor_resume_for_job(self, job):
        company_info = self.agents["research"].think_and_act(company_name=job["company"])
        tailored = self.agents["tailor"].think_and_act(resume=self.resume, job=job, company=company_info)
        ats_score = self.agents["ats"].think_and_act(resume=tailored, job=job)
        return tailored, ats_score

5. Example Agent: JobSearchAgent

python
from .base_agent import BaseAgent
from .tools.tool_registry import get_tool_registry

class JobSearchAgent(BaseAgent):
    def __init__(self):
        tools = get_tool_registry()
        super().__init__("JobSearchAgent", tools={"search_jobs": tools["search_jobs"]})

    def think_and_act(self, keywords, location):
        self.observe(f"Searching jobs for {keywords} in {location}")
        jobs = self.act("search_jobs", keywords=keywords, location=location)
        return jobs

6. Example Agent: TailoringAgent

python
from .base_agent import BaseAgent
from .tools.tool_registry import get_tool_registry

class TailoringAgent(BaseAgent):
    def __init__(self):
        tools = get_tool_registry()
        super().__init__("TailoringAgent", tools={
            "tailor_resume": tools["tailor_resume"],
            "embed_text": tools["embed_text"]
        })

    def think_and_act(self, resume, job, company):
        self.observe(f"Tailoring resume for {job['title']} at {company['name']}")
        tailored_resume = self.act("tailor_resume", resume=resume, job=job, company=company)
        return tailored_resume

7. Agent Memory (optional but powerful)

Inside agents/memory/:

  • Short-term memory: Current conversation context or task state (per run).

  • Long-term memory: Past searches, user preferences, embedding cache.

This allows persistent context e.g., the system remembers past jobs the user liked.

Example minimal memory store:

python
import json

class MemoryStore:
    def __init__(self, path="data/memory.json"):
        self.path = path
        self.data = self._load()

    def _load(self):
        try:
            with open(self.path) as f:
                return json.load(f)
        except FileNotFoundError:
            return {}

    def save(self):
        with open(self.path, "w") as f:
            json.dump(self.data, f, indent=2)

    def get(self, key, default=None):
        return self.data.get(key, default)

    def set(self, key, value):
        self.data[key] = value
        self.save()

If you want full agent capabilities (like LangChain, LlamaIndex, or CrewAI), this structure is compatible.

  • Move your tools into the format these frameworks expect (Tool or FunctionTool objects).

  • The rest of your app (GUI, orchestrator) remains unchanged.

You said:
If workers folder is for DB, storage, and caching, then what is the memory folder for?
ChatGPT said:

Excellent distinction and youre asking exactly the right kind of question.

Lets clarify this fully, because memory and storage/cache (workers/storage folders) sound similar but serve very different purposes in an agentic AI system.

TL;DR The Key Difference

ConceptPurposeType of DataLifespanTypical Users
storage/ (and DB/cache handled by workers/)Persistent application data resumes, cached job listings, embeddings, database records.Objective data (files, jobs, embeddings, user prefs).Long-term (days years).Whole app (backend, scrapers, etc.).
agents/memory/Contextual AI reasoning memory what the agents remember while reasoning or across sessions.Subjective data (observations, goals, thoughts, results).Short-term (per run) or symbolic long-term (via vector DB).AI agents only.

So:

  • storage/ system memory, like a database.

  • agents/memory/ cognitive memory, like an agents brain or working context.

In Detail

1. storage/ and workers/

These handle externalized, structured, persistent data used by the whole app.

Purpose

  • Cache job postings and scraping results.

  • Store user resumes, embeddings, and preferences.

  • Manage async IO, database writes, background sync.

Examples

python
# storage/cache.py
import sqlite3

def store_job(job_id, job_json):
    conn = sqlite3.connect("data/app.db")
    cur = conn.cursor()
    cur.execute("INSERT OR REPLACE INTO jobs VALUES (?, ?)", (job_id, json.dumps(job_json)))
    conn.commit()
    conn.close()

Used by

  • Job fetchers

  • Scoring pipeline

  • Embedding service

  • Controller

Think of this as the hard drive for the application.

2. agents/memory/

This manages the agents reasoning context what it knows, noticed, and decided recently or across sessions.

Purpose

  • Store the agents short-term thoughts and plans.

  • Maintain context between multiple actions (I searched for jobs, I scored these, I tailored this one).

  • Optionally keep long-term knowledge (like embeddings of user preferences) for continual improvement.

Examples

python
# agents/memory/memory_store.py
class MemoryStore:
    def __init__(self):
        self.short_term = []
        self.long_term = {}

    def observe(self, message):
        self.short_term.append(message)

    def recall(self, key):
        return self.long_term.get(key)

    def remember(self, key, value):
        self.long_term[key] = value

Then in an agent:

python
self.memory.observe(f"Searched jobs for '{keywords}' and found {len(jobs)} results.")

Used by

  • Agents during reasoning (JobSearchAgent, TailoringAgent, etc.).

  • AgentOrchestrator when chaining agents.

  • Could store lessons learned (like user preferences, scoring thresholds).

Think of this as the short-term memory + working memory of your AI system comparable to the context window or episodic memory in an LLM agent.

Relationship Between Them

Heres how they interact:

wasm
             
              GUI / Controller     
             
                       
                       
             
              Agent Orchestrator   
             
                       
     
                                       
 JobSearchAgent   TailoringAgent     ATSAgent
                                       
                                       
  (memory)          (memory)          (memory)
                                       
                                       
(storage/cache)  workers/db

  • agents/memory/ stores reasoning context (observations, intermediate thoughts).

  • storage/ stores data results (resumes, jobs, embeddings, ATS scores).

  • The workers/ may asynchronously write from memory to storage (e.g., saving summaries or embeddings).

Example Scenario

Suppose a user uploads a resume and searches for Data Scientist, Toronto.

StepWhat Happens in MemoryWhat Happens in Storage
User uploads resumeAgent memory notes: Loaded resume with 5 years ML experience.Resume text saved in DB. Embedding stored in vector table.
JobSearchAgent searches jobsMemory: Found 72 jobs from Indeed API.Job JSON cached in SQLite.
ScoringAgent evaluates jobsMemory: stores top 10 job IDs and scores for reasoning.Full score results saved to DB for reuse.
User selects one jobMemory: User chose Job #7 (NLP Engineer).No change.
TailoringAgent tailors resumeMemory stores context for prompt (This job needs NLP + Python + AWS).Tailored resume saved as DOCX/PDF.
ATSAgent simulates scoringMemory adds ATS score and improvement tips.Final ATS score logged in DB.

So the agents memory is narrative/contextual, while storage is factual/persistent.

Bonus: How They Can Work Together

If you want persistent agent memory, you can connect them:

python
# agents/memory/context_window.py
from storage.cache import store_agent_memory

class ContextWindow:
    def __init__(self, memory_store):
        self.memory = memory_store

    def persist(self):
        store_agent_memory(self.memory.long_term)

That way, an agents experience (e.g., knowing the user prefers remote jobs) is saved across sessions.

3. Layer-by-Layer Purpose Breakdown

config/

Centralized configuration and prompt management.

  • settings.py: loads API keys, model names, thresholds.

  • prompts/: reusable prompt templates for LLMs (tailoring, ATS, research).

gui/

Front-end layer built with Tkinter.

  • Modularized into small view classes.

  • Non-blocking updates (worker callbacks).

  • Custom widgets and diff views.

controller/

Bridges GUI with the agentic backend.

  • Event-driven architecture.

  • Orchestrates pipeline (resume jobs tailoring).

  • Handles errors and retries gracefully.

agents/

The agentic AI brain.

  • Each agent focuses on one subtask.

  • The agent_orchestrator.py coordinates multi-step workflows.

  • Agents use tools to act on data.

Memory system

  • short_term.py: per-session context (whats currently being worked on).

  • long_term.py: persists key insights (e.g., user skill preferences).

  • memory_manager.py: unified interface between short-term and long-term.

Tools system

  • Each *_tools.py file exposes one type of AI capability.

  • The tool_registry.py registers these for agent use.

  • Tools internally call logic from core/.

core/

The backbone domain-specific business logic.

  • Pure functions with minimal dependencies.

  • No UI or orchestration logic here.

  • Can be unit-tested independently.

Each subfolder focuses on one business capability:

  • parsing: resume/job parsing.

  • scoring: similarity scoring and explanations.

  • tailoring: LLM & rules-based resume tailoring.

  • ats: ATS simulation and feedback.

  • research: company research.

  • embeddings: text embeddings and vector stores.

storage/

Handles persistence, caching, and encryption.

  • database.py: SQLite or SQLAlchemy ORM.

  • cache_manager.py: local job posting cache (avoid repeated scrapes).

  • file_store.py: handles file uploads and saving tailored resumes.

  • encryption.py: AES/Fernet encryption for PII.

workers/

Manages asynchronous, background operations.

  • ThreadPoolExecutor for scraping or LLM calls.

  • Job queue system for scaling heavy tasks.

  • monitor.py: simple progress and error tracking.

utils/

Small helper utilities and cross-cutting concerns.

  • Logging, configuration loading, retry decorators, etc.

  • Used across all layers.

tests/

Comprehensive testing suite.

  • Organized per-module (agents, tools, parsers, GUI, etc.).

  • Uses mocks for network/LLM calls.

  • Fixtures for reproducible test data.

assets/

Static resources:

  • Icons, fonts, and templates for resume exports.

bash

     agents/agent_orchestrator.py
         JobSearchAgent
             tools/scraping_tools.py
             storage/cache_manager.py
         ScoringAgent
             tools/embedding_tools.py
             core/scoring/similarity_scorer.py
         TailoringAgent
             tools/tailoring_tools.py
             core/tailoring/tailoring_engine.py
             config/prompts/tailoring_prompt.txt
         ATSAgent
             tools/ats_tools.py
             core/ats/ats_simulator.py
         ResearchAgent
             tools/research_tools.py
             core/research/company_researcher.py

Each agents tools call into core/ logic, and all long-term data (resumes, jobs, embeddings) are stored via storage/.

5. Guiding Principles for This Architecture

PrincipleImplementation
Modular DesignEach folder represents a functional domain.
Single ResponsibilityEach file handles exactly one job.
Separation of ConcernsGUI Controller Agent Core Storage layers.
Agentic AI AbstractionAll intelligent behavior lives under agents/.
TestabilityCore logic and tools are easily unit-testable.
ExtensibilityAdd new agents (e.g., CoverLetterAgent) without breaking structure.
Security FirstEncryption + data privacy layers isolated in storage/.
Async SafeLong-running tasks offloaded to workers/.
